Wonderful, delicious Mexican inspired spot! One of my favorite places we have visited this trip to NYC. Very nice food and good cocktails as well. The whole atmosphere when you walk in is light and beautiful, really adding to the experience.  Highlights for me: pescado taco, elote, chips and guacamole.  All of the food was good, but to elevate just a bit more, I’d change a few small things. The pozole was good, but a bit too spicy to eat. It would be very nice complemented with a tortilla or type of bread, still staying true to Mexican cuisine. Also, the two meat tacos - I would’ve preferred just a bit less meat and more condiments to compliment the tastes.  Excellent service, which is always appreciated. The server we had clearly loved the restaurant and was able to genuinely give recommendations and information about the menu. Always a plus.  Pricing: to me, pretty reasonable, especially for NYC. You can get plenty of food for $10-15 if that’s what you want to shoot for. 3 tacos is $12.  Will definitely return and recommend this restaurant to others! Thanks Oso!  #oso #mexican #tacos #elote #pozolerojo #pescado #barbacoa #lengua #newyork #ny #nyc

WHY 3 STARS 🌟: The reason for 3 stars instead of a higher rating is due to the inconsistency of the overall experience which didn't carry over when I visited during evening shift. Interesting how some chefs want to kill you.  I ordered the fish tacos (fried), the mole (on chicken) and the barbacoa.  All bland.  Sorry!  The mile is a sauce poured over shredded chicken.  When the meat is cooked separately from the sauce then u don't get that amazing combination of juices (animal fat) mixing together.  The fish taco - you usually taste just the fried.  I didn't taste either. The barbacoa was my favorite and usually it is my least. But all beautifully presented. Womp womp. I will say this:  some of the best tortillas in nyc.  They do tortillas right!

Oso is an instant favorite and hope to get back there ASAP. Firstly: Hands down the best Mole I've found outside of Mexico -- quite possibly overall. Served in a taco made with one of the best homemade tortillas I've had and it's a phenomenal dish I'm still dreaming about 36 hours later. The barbacoa taco is very remarkable too; barbacoa being one of my family's mainstays, I've got a wide frame of reference. Oso's is successfully succulent, savory, and soft to the palate -- one inhales it and quickly orders seconds. To round out my taco order: lengua -- a delicate option only attempted by a bold Mexican restaurant -- and Oso's interpretation does not disappoint. A wonderful marriage of flavors both sweet and savory are driven home with a unique tenderness that almost melts in your mouth. As an appetizer I had the pozole verde and it was quite tasty, refreshing, and satisfying. To round out my meal, the intricate Coup de Khan cocktail provided a smoky, sweet, and sour refresher. Others in my brunch group ordered the enchiladas, chilaquiles rojos, and quesadillas and were all very, very content. One person even managed to have room for dessert and had a very enviable order of churros I hope to get next visit. You know a meal is amazing when no one says anything because they're busy eating. Thank you for a great meal, Oso.

Oso is not your average neighborhood dining establishment. For now, it's a well-kept secret, a gem in the heart of an already fantastic neighborhood, and the kind of place that exudes warmth and friendliness--whether you sidle up to the bar for late night cocktails, or grab a group for a celebratory meal! Mark my words, though...it won't be a secret for long.  Pro-tip: come hungry and do the menu up right. Start with some house-made guacamole and tortilla chips while you deliberate, begin with a salad and a couple tacos as appetizers (they're perfect to whet your appetite for what's next), and dig into the real stars of the menu--the entreé section! The guava glazed ribs with pickled veggies go perfectly with a side of the Elote (street corn), or grab a whole fish of the day! (Ask your server to deep-fry the spine when you're finished. You'll get major foodie points for being in the know...) The evening would not be complete without having a Crema Mezcal and the Mexican Brownie with Horchata ice cream for dessert.  Also--the cocktail program here is SICK. If you want a fantastic spin on a classic cocktail, the menu will not disappoint. If you want to be the coolest person in your friend group...start building your knowledge of Tequila and Mezcal. You can take a top-shelf or basic flight in either, and the prices are really reasonable.  All in all: the music and ambience in this place are awesome, the food tastes as close to the streets of Mexico City as you'll find around NYC, everything in this spot is made from scratch, and when you're hanging at Oso--it's always a good time.

Not to mention the cocktails, which were extremely impressive. I can't wait to try their brunch menu!!! Thank you Oso for being awesome. :)
